242
00:28:25,288 --> 00:28:27,791
You ain't got a brain in your skull.

243
00:28:29,626 --> 00:28:33,046
<i>Why, we're in the money
I'll bet we're in the money</i>

244
00:28:33,213 --> 00:28:37,133
<i>We've got a lot of what it takes
To get along</i>

245
00:28:37,884 --> 00:28:39,803
On account of you, I killed a man.

246
00:28:39,969 --> 00:28:43,473
And now we're all gonna be wanted
for murder, and that's you too, boy.

247
00:28:44,974 --> 00:28:48,686
<i>We never see a headline
About a bread line today</i>

248
00:28:48,853 --> 00:28:52,690
<i>And when we see the landlord
We can look that guy right in the eye</i>

249
00:28:53,650 --> 00:28:55,568
Dummy! Stupid!

250
00:28:55,735 --> 00:28:56,736
Shhh.

251
00:28:56,903 --> 00:28:58,530
What was you thinking about?

252
00:29:00,990 --> 00:29:03,743
Do a dumb-ass thing like that again,
boy, and I'm gonna kill you.

253
00:29:03,910 --> 00:29:09,207
Shh! If you boys wanna talk,
why don't y'all go outside?

254
00:29:11,167 --> 00:29:14,504
<i>- Hey, who are you?
- You'll find out.</i>

255
00:29:14,671 --> 00:29:17,090
<i>Come on, boys,
we might as well begin right here.</i>

256
00:29:17,257 --> 00:29:19,175
<i>All right, come over here.</i>

257
00:29:23,763 --> 00:29:25,974
<i>We're in the money</i>

258
00:29:26,141 --> 00:29:27,517
<i>We're in the money</i>

259
00:29:29,519 --> 00:29:31,521
We've got a--

260
00:29:33,481 --> 00:29:36,443
<i>We've got a lot of what it take--</i>

261
00:29:38,027 --> 00:29:40,196
<i>We've got a lot of what it takes</i>

262
00:29:40,363 --> 00:29:42,198
- To get along
CLYDE: Bonnie.

263
00:29:42,365 --> 00:29:44,367
Hey-- Hey, honey.

264
00:29:48,246 --> 00:29:53,042
Honey, come on, I wanna talk to you
for just a minute. Sit down, huh?

265
00:29:53,710 --> 00:29:55,086
Look...

266
00:29:57,297 --> 00:30:00,550
This afternoon we killed a man,
and we were seen.

267
00:30:00,717 --> 00:30:02,510
So far, nobody knows who you are...

268
00:30:02,677 --> 00:30:06,055
...but they know who I am. They'll be
after me and anybody who's with me.

269
00:30:06,222 --> 00:30:08,224
That's murder.
Now it's gonna get rough.

270
00:30:08,391 --> 00:30:11,060
Now, look, I can't get out,
but right now you still can.

271
00:30:11,227 --> 00:30:14,814
You say the word, and I'll put you
on that bus back to your mama...

272
00:30:14,981 --> 00:30:18,526
...because you mean a lot to me, and
I ain't gonna make you run with me.

273
00:30:22,280 --> 00:30:23,907
- No.
- Huh?

274
00:30:26,618 --> 00:30:27,660
No.

275
00:30:27,911 --> 00:30:30,580
I ain't a rich man.
You could get a rich man if you tried.

276
00:30:30,747 --> 00:30:33,791
I don't want no rich man.

277
00:30:39,964 --> 00:30:42,091
You ain't gonna
have a minute's peace.

278
00:30:42,717 --> 00:30:43,760
You promise?

279
00:33:24,754 --> 00:33:27,882
Hah. At least I ain't a liar.

280
00:33:40,103 --> 00:33:42,897
I told you I wasn't no lover boy.

281
00:34:04,669 --> 00:34:05,962
Oh!

282
00:34:12,301 --> 00:34:16,639
- Let me look at you, boy.
- Hey, hey, come on, now.

283
00:34:16,806 --> 00:34:18,182
Come on. Oh!

284
00:34:20,727 --> 00:34:22,603
Boy, you can do better than that.

285
00:34:26,858 --> 00:34:28,901
- Hey.
- Hey, hey, how's Mama?

286
00:34:29,068 --> 00:34:30,069
Fine, fine.

287
00:34:30,236 --> 00:34:31,988
- Sister? Sister?
- Sent her best to you.

288
00:34:32,155 --> 00:34:36,367
- Filling out there. Must be that prison food.
- No, no, no, that's-- That's married life.

289
00:34:36,534 --> 00:34:38,494
You know what they say...

290
00:34:38,661 --> 00:34:41,622
...it's the face powder
that gets a man interested...

291
00:34:41,789 --> 00:34:44,751
...but it's the baking powder
that keeps him home. Huh?

292
00:34:47,170 --> 00:34:50,673
I want you to meet my wife, Blanche.
Blanche, this is my baby brother.

293
00:34:50,840 --> 00:34:53,760
- How you doing? It's real nice to know you.
- How do you do?

294
00:34:53,926 --> 00:34:57,180
- Heh. Yeah. Hey, Bonnie!
- Yeah.

295
00:34:57,346 --> 00:34:59,348
Hey. Hey, Bonnie! Hey.

296
00:34:59,807 --> 00:35:02,852
- Hey.
- Hey! Wait. Is it--?

297
00:35:03,019 --> 00:35:06,355
Oh, boy. Is this Bonnie?

298
00:35:06,522 --> 00:35:09,150
Hear you're taking good care
of the baby of the family.

299
00:35:09,317 --> 00:35:12,737
Sis, I'm just so glad to meet you. Come on.
I want you to meet my wife.

300
00:35:12,904 --> 00:35:16,199
- Blanche, this here is Bonnie.
- Hi.

301
00:35:16,365 --> 00:35:17,700
Hello.

302
00:35:17,867 --> 00:35:19,702
Hey, everybody, this is C.W. Moss.

303
00:35:20,203 --> 00:35:22,371
My brother, Buck, and his wife, Blanche.

304
00:35:22,538 --> 00:35:25,708
Howdy, everybody. Howdy, y'all.

305
00:35:26,167 --> 00:35:30,421
Howdy, Mrs. Barrow. Or may I call you--?
May I call you Blanche? Heh.

306
00:35:30,588 --> 00:35:34,425
I sure am pleased to meet you. How'd you
find us here in the neck of the woods?

307
00:35:34,592 --> 00:35:37,386
Boy, you sure--
You sure picked a good day for it.

308
00:35:37,553 --> 00:35:39,055
Oh, is that a new <i>Screenland Magazine?</i>

309
00:35:40,598 --> 00:35:42,892
Is there any new pictures of
Myrna Loy in there?

310
00:35:43,059 --> 00:35:45,269
She's my favorite picture star. May I?

311
00:35:46,103 --> 00:35:48,314
Let me get the Kodak.
We'll take some pictures.

312
00:35:48,481 --> 00:35:50,358
Put your pants on.
We'll take some pictures.

313
00:35:50,525 --> 00:35:52,693
Come on Blanche, get out of there!

314
00:35:52,860 --> 00:35:55,613
I'm a mess.
Been driving all day, honey.

315
00:35:55,780 --> 00:35:59,242
- Come on, now. Come on, now.
- Now hold onto her there.

316
00:35:59,408 --> 00:36:01,577
- You're not a--
- I got it.

317
00:36:01,744 --> 00:36:06,833
Did you take my picture, Buck? Well, I
declare. I asked you not to take my picture.

318
00:36:06,999 --> 00:36:08,960
Hey, Buck, get one of this.

319
00:36:09,126 --> 00:36:12,088
Hey, brother, I wanna talk
to you later on.

320
00:36:13,631 --> 00:36:15,550
You devil, you.

321
00:36:16,259 --> 00:36:17,885
Hold it.

322
00:36:19,387 --> 00:36:20,721
- You got that? Ha-ha.
- Yeah.

323
00:36:20,888 --> 00:36:23,850
Hey, now you take one
of me and my missus, here, Clyde.

324
00:36:24,016 --> 00:36:25,935
- All right.
- Honey, I don't wanna.

325
00:36:26,102 --> 00:36:29,438
Honestly, I don't want--
I don't want my picture taken.

326
00:36:29,605 --> 00:36:32,191
- You look over there at the birdy and smile.
- Buck.

327
00:36:32,358 --> 00:36:35,027
- Give old-- Give old--
- Be serious. Be serious.

328
00:36:35,653 --> 00:36:37,405
Hold still.

329
00:36:38,614 --> 00:36:42,660
Hey, let me take one of Bonnie alone.
Come on, honey.

330
00:36:42,827 --> 00:36:44,620
Okay.

331
00:36:48,457 --> 00:36:50,334
All right, now. Oh, honey. Heh.

332
00:36:51,460 --> 00:36:54,672
- Hey. Come on now, a little smile.
- No.

333
00:36:54,839 --> 00:36:55,965
Don't wanna smile?

334
00:36:56,132 --> 00:36:58,175
Eh?

335
00:36:58,342 --> 00:37:01,345
I wanna have a chat with you.
C.W., take the girls' pictures.

336
00:37:01,512 --> 00:37:04,140
Why don't you step
in there with Bonnie?

337
00:37:04,307 --> 00:37:07,268
- What'd you think or her? Yeah.
- Bonnie?

338
00:37:08,436 --> 00:37:09,896
She's a peach.

339
00:37:11,564 --> 00:37:13,274
Hey, now.

340
00:37:15,735 --> 00:37:18,487
- Now. Now tell me true.
- What?

341
00:37:19,030 --> 00:37:20,531
What?

342
00:37:20,990 --> 00:37:23,159
Is she as good as she looks?

343
00:37:25,828 --> 00:37:27,163
She's better.

344
00:37:34,462 --> 00:37:37,173
Hey, listen, it was
either you or him, wasn't it?

345
00:37:37,340 --> 00:37:39,425
- What?
- The guy you killed, you had to do it?

346
00:37:39,592 --> 00:37:42,011
- It was you or him.
- He put me on the spot. I had to.

347
00:37:42,178 --> 00:37:44,931
- You had to do it, right?
- I had to. I had to.

348
00:37:45,723 --> 00:37:49,518
I knew you did. Don't say
anything to Blanche about that.

349
00:37:49,685 --> 00:37:51,520
Oh, uh...

350
00:37:51,687 --> 00:37:55,358
Hey, that time you broke out of jail,
that true she talk you into going back?

351
00:37:55,524 --> 00:37:57,818
- Yeah. You hear about that?
- Is that true?

352
00:37:57,985 --> 00:37:59,820
Yeah, yeah.

353
00:38:00,196 --> 00:38:02,907
Well, I won't say
nothing to Bonnie about it.

354
00:38:03,074 --> 00:38:05,201
I appreciate that.

355
00:38:15,586 --> 00:38:18,339
- We're gonna have ourselves a time, boy!
- We surely are.

356
00:38:22,301 --> 00:38:23,552
Yeah.

357
00:38:25,721 --> 00:38:27,640
What are we gonna do?

358
00:38:28,599 --> 00:38:30,977
Well, how's this?

359
00:38:31,143 --> 00:38:36,107
I figured we all drive up in Missouri.
They ain't looking for me up there.

360
00:38:36,273 --> 00:38:40,069
We find a nice little place to hole up in.
We have us a regular vacation.

361
00:38:40,236 --> 00:38:42,446
- All right?
- Yeah, yeah.

362
00:38:44,573 --> 00:38:48,160
- No trouble now.
- I ain't looking to go back to no prison.

363
00:38:48,327 --> 00:38:52,081
I heard in prison you had a little trouble.
You was cutting on your toes.

364
00:38:52,248 --> 00:38:54,208
Really? You heard about that, eh?

365
00:38:54,375 --> 00:38:56,377
Yeah, well, I did a little toe-cutting.

366
00:38:56,544 --> 00:38:59,588
That ain't half of it.
I did it so I could get off of work detail.

367
00:38:59,755 --> 00:39:01,924
Breaking them rocks
with a sledgehammer.

368
00:39:02,091 --> 00:39:05,636
And you know what?
The very next week I get paroled.

369
00:39:05,803 --> 00:39:08,055
I walk out of that
God forsaken jail on crutches.

370
00:39:10,057 --> 00:39:12,935
- Ain't life grand?
- Shoot.

371
00:39:21,027 --> 00:39:25,114
Hey, you wanna hear a story? About
this boy, he owned a dairy farm, see.

372
00:39:25,281 --> 00:39:27,575
And his old ma, she was
kind of sick, you know.

373
00:39:27,742 --> 00:39:30,911
And the doctor, he called
him over and said:

374
00:39:31,078 --> 00:39:35,916
"Listen, your ma, she lying there,
she's just so sick and she's weakly...

375
00:39:36,083 --> 00:39:39,462
...and I want you to try to persuade
her to take a little brandy, see.

376
00:39:39,628 --> 00:39:41,630
Just to pick her spirits up, you know."

377
00:39:41,797 --> 00:39:46,802
And, "Ma's a teetotaler," he says,
"she wouldn't touch a drop."

378
00:39:46,969 --> 00:39:49,513
"Well, I'll tell you what you do."
That's the doc.

379
00:39:49,680 --> 00:39:52,058
"Now, I tell you what you do.

380
00:39:52,224 --> 00:39:54,643
You bring in a
fresh quart of milk every day...

381
00:39:54,810 --> 00:39:57,855
...and you put some brandy in it, see.
And you try that."

382
00:39:58,022 --> 00:40:02,610
So he did, and he doctored it all up
with the brandy, the fresh milk...

383
00:40:02,777 --> 00:40:06,489
...and he gave it to his mama, she drank
a little bit of it. She didn't--

384
00:40:06,655 --> 00:40:11,077
So next day he brought it in again,
and she drank a little more, you know.

385
00:40:11,243 --> 00:40:15,289
And so, it went on that way for--
The third day, just a little more...

386
00:40:15,456 --> 00:40:18,584
...and the fourth day she was,
you know, took a little bit more...

387
00:40:18,751 --> 00:40:22,254
...and then finally one week later,
he gave her the milk...

388
00:40:22,421 --> 00:40:25,800
...and she just drank it down, boy.
She swallowed the whole thing...

389
00:40:25,966 --> 00:40:28,177
...and she called him over and she said,
"Son...

390
00:40:28,344 --> 00:40:31,388
...whatever you do, don't sell that cow."

391
00:40:36,894 --> 00:40:38,687
"Don't sell the cow."

392
00:40:44,693 --> 00:40:47,196
- You got the keys now, haven't you?
- Yeah, I got them.

393
00:40:47,363 --> 00:40:48,781
Fine.

394
00:40:57,790 --> 00:41:00,209
Bye-bye.
- Bye.

395
00:41:04,588 --> 00:41:06,423
I gave him a month's rent in advance.

396
00:41:06,590 --> 00:41:08,884
We're all set. Let's get inside.

397
00:41:12,471 --> 00:41:14,890
Honey lamb, I'm taking
you to our first home. Ha-ha!

398
00:41:15,224 --> 00:41:17,184
Here comes the bride.

399
00:41:17,351 --> 00:41:19,311
What do you think, hon? Huh?

400
00:41:20,229 --> 00:41:22,565
Just perfect.

401
00:41:22,815 --> 00:41:24,024
This is your first home.

402
00:41:26,485 --> 00:41:28,904
Well, he gave me the grocery number.

403
00:41:29,071 --> 00:41:32,116
This is perfect for all of us, isn't it?

404
00:41:35,786 --> 00:41:38,038
4-3-3-7, please.

405
00:41:38,205 --> 00:41:42,042
- Hi, there, Speedie's Groceries?
- Look, it's so clean, Buck.

406
00:41:42,209 --> 00:41:46,380
- And a Frigidaire, not an icebox.
- 143 Hillsdale Avenue.

407
00:41:46,547 --> 00:41:47,631
Hillsdale Avenue.

408
00:41:47,798 --> 00:41:50,259
Oh. They got linoleum on the counter.

409
00:41:50,426 --> 00:41:52,636
- Ain't that clever?
- Eight pounds of pork chops.

410
00:41:52,803 --> 00:41:57,266
Four pounds of red beans.
Some Chase and Sanborn coffee.

411
00:41:57,433 --> 00:41:59,435
About eight bottles of Dr. Pepper.

412
00:42:11,280 --> 00:42:13,949
You sure can play checkers.

413
00:42:18,454 --> 00:42:20,080
You're killing me.

414
00:42:22,333 --> 00:42:25,377
You need a haircut. You're
looking just like a hillbilly boy.

415
00:42:25,544 --> 00:42:27,504
You are just like an old man.

416
00:42:27,671 --> 00:42:31,133
Playing checkers all the time,
don't pay any attention to your poor wife.

417
00:42:31,300 --> 00:42:34,136
Boy, you ain't gonna never beat me,
but you just keep trying.

418
00:42:34,553 --> 00:42:35,888
Come on, I'm gonna whip you.

419
00:42:36,055 --> 00:42:37,223
on, Daddy...

420
00:42:37,389 --> 00:42:39,975
...you sure do need a haircut.

421
00:42:40,142 --> 00:42:43,312
Why, you look just like a little
old hillbilly, I do declare.

422
00:42:43,479 --> 00:42:46,440
Oh, mercy me, don't.

423
00:42:46,607 --> 00:42:49,526
Don't talk that way when she's
right there in the next room.

424
00:42:49,693 --> 00:42:52,571
There is always somebody
in the next room, in this room...

425
00:42:52,738 --> 00:42:54,949
...or in every other kind of room.

426
00:42:55,115 --> 00:42:59,036
Well, honey, don't you ever
just wanna be alone with me?

427
00:42:59,370 --> 00:43:01,413
Well, I always feel like we're alone.

428
00:43:03,165 --> 00:43:04,583
Do you, baby?

429
00:43:04,917 --> 00:43:06,752
I'm hungry. Hey, Buck.

430
00:43:19,223 --> 00:43:21,100
Groceries, ma'am.

431
00:43:22,893 --> 00:43:26,188
- How much?
- Six dollars and 43 cents.

432
00:43:31,193 --> 00:43:33,612
- Forty-three?
- Yes, ma'am.

433
00:43:35,948 --> 00:43:37,658
All right.

434
00:43:39,785 --> 00:43:42,913
- There you are.
- Okay.

435
00:43:43,289 --> 00:43:46,208
- Let me help. Those bags are heavy.
- No, thanks, I'll get them.

436
00:43:46,375 --> 00:43:48,585
- Yes, ma'am.
- Just get the door.

437
00:43:48,752 --> 00:43:49,878
Yes, ma'am.

438
00:43:50,087 --> 00:43:51,714
Buck, look at Bonnie. Get that--

439
00:43:51,880 --> 00:43:53,674
Shh. He's still down there.

440
00:43:53,841 --> 00:43:55,217
Close the door.

441
00:44:05,853 --> 00:44:08,397
<i>But few of them really are justified</i>

442
00:44:08,564 --> 00:44:11,734
<i>If you get right down to the point.</i>

443
00:44:11,900 --> 00:44:16,238
<i>You've heard of a woman's glory
Being spent on a downright cur--</i>

444
00:44:16,405 --> 00:44:18,157
Did you write all that yourself?

445
00:44:18,324 --> 00:44:20,784
Do you wanna hear this or not?

446
00:44:21,452 --> 00:44:22,453
--cur.

447
00:44:22,619 --> 00:44:28,709
<i>Still you can't always judge the story
As true, being told by her.</i>

448
00:44:31,295 --> 00:44:34,423
<i>Now Sal was a gal of rare beauty</i>

449
00:44:34,590 --> 00:44:36,800
<i>Though her features were coarse
and tough--</i>

450
00:44:36,967 --> 00:44:38,302
I knew that old gal.

451
00:44:38,469 --> 00:44:41,347
She was cockeyed
and she had a harelip and no teeth.

452
00:44:42,097 --> 00:44:44,224
Hey, Buck, come on, now.
Go ahead.

453
00:44:44,391 --> 00:44:47,186
<i>Now Sal was</i> a <i>gal of rare beauty</i>

454
00:44:47,353 --> 00:44:50,230
<i>Though her features were coarse and tough</i>

455
00:44:50,397 --> 00:44:52,858
<i>She never once faltered from duty</i>

456
00:44:53,025 --> 00:44:55,611
<i>To play on the up and up.</i>

457
00:44:56,195 --> 00:44:59,406
<i>Sal told me this tale on the evening</i>

458
00:44:59,573 --> 00:45:02,409
<i>Before she was turned out free.</i>

459
00:45:02,576 --> 00:45:06,705
<i>And I'll do my best to relate it
Just as she told it to me.</i>

460
00:45:06,872 --> 00:45:10,292
Hey, hey. The laws are outside.
They're blocking the driveway.

461
00:45:26,225 --> 00:45:27,976
- Buck, get us out of here!
- Shut up!

462
00:45:30,354 --> 00:45:32,481
They got us blocked.
We gotta get the car out.

463
00:45:38,737 --> 00:45:39,863
Cover me!

464
00:45:43,909 --> 00:45:45,411
Get out of here.

465
00:46:13,272 --> 00:46:15,315
Where's Blanche? Where's Blanche?

466
00:46:34,626 --> 00:46:36,920
Damn it, you almost got us killed!

467
00:46:37,546 --> 00:46:41,133
What did I do wrong? I thought
you'd be happy if I got shot!

468
00:46:41,300 --> 00:46:44,386
Yeah! Yeah, it would've
saved us all a lot of trouble.

469
00:46:44,553 --> 00:46:46,930
Buck, don't let that woman
talk to me like that.

470
00:46:47,097 --> 00:46:50,893
You shouldn't have done that, Blanche.
It was a dumb thing to do.

471
00:46:51,477 --> 00:46:54,980
Oh, Buck, please, I didn't marry you
to see you get shot, honey.

472
00:46:55,147 --> 00:46:58,066
Let's go. Let's leave.
Let's get out of here and leave town.

473
00:46:58,233 --> 00:47:00,319
Please make him stop
the car and let us out.

474
00:47:00,486 --> 00:47:02,362
I can't.

475
00:47:02,571 --> 00:47:04,239
I killed a guy. Now we're in this.

476
00:47:05,574 --> 00:47:07,618
- Please?!
'Wm you shut up?!

477
00:47:08,160 --> 00:47:10,996
Shut up your big mouth! At least
do that much. Shut up!

478
00:47:11,163 --> 00:47:13,123
Cut it out, Bonnie!

479
00:47:14,875 --> 00:47:17,586
You stop the car.
I wanna talk to you.

480
00:47:34,228 --> 00:47:36,188
- Get-- Get rid of her.
- I can't get--

481
00:47:36,355 --> 00:47:38,273
- She's Buck's wife.
- Get rid of them both.

482
00:47:38,440 --> 00:47:41,860
- Why? What's the matter with you?
- She is what's the matter with me.

483
00:47:42,027 --> 00:47:44,655
She-- She's nothing but a dumb, stupid...

484
00:47:44,821 --> 00:47:46,198
-...Sanborn hick.
- Look!

485
00:47:46,448 --> 00:47:48,033
She ain't got a brain in her head.

486
00:47:48,200 --> 00:47:50,160
What makes you better?
You so damn special?

487
00:47:50,327 --> 00:47:53,872
You were a West Dallas waitress.
Spent your time picking up truck drivers.

488
00:47:54,039 --> 00:47:55,582
Stop it!

489
00:47:55,749 --> 00:47:59,378
Oh, big Clyde Barrow!
You're just like your brother!

490
00:47:59,545 --> 00:48:01,964
- Uh-huh.
- Ignorant, uneducated hillbilly!

491
00:48:02,130 --> 00:48:05,634
The only special thing about you
is your peculiar ideas about lovemaking...

492
00:48:05,801 --> 00:48:07,844
...which is no lovemaking at all.

493
00:48:19,273 --> 00:48:20,315
No.

494
00:48:20,649 --> 00:48:23,986
Oh, Clyde, please, I didn't mean that.

495
00:48:24,152 --> 00:48:28,156
Listen, it was just all--
All that shooting...

496
00:48:28,323 --> 00:48:32,703
...and all those guns. I got so scared.
Please, honey, I didn't mean it.

497
00:48:33,662 --> 00:48:34,997
Yeah, honey.

498
00:48:38,375 --> 00:48:39,626
Come on.

499
00:49:16,538 --> 00:49:17,873
"Law enforcement officers...

500
00:49:18,040 --> 00:49:20,917
...throughout the Southwest
are frankly amazed...

501
00:49:21,084 --> 00:49:24,254
...at the way in which the
will-0'-the-wisp bandit Clyde Barrow...

502
00:49:24,421 --> 00:49:27,049
...and his yellow-haired companion,
Bonnie Parker...

503
00:49:27,215 --> 00:49:30,093
...continue to elude
their would-be captors.

504
00:49:30,260 --> 00:49:35,432
Since engaging in a police battle
on the streets of Joplin, Missouri...

505
00:49:35,599 --> 00:49:38,310
...and slaying three of their number.

506
00:49:38,477 --> 00:49:42,397
The Barrow Gang has been reported
as far west as Whites City, New Mexico...

507
00:49:42,564 --> 00:49:44,900
...and as far north as Chicago.

508
00:49:46,526 --> 00:49:50,697
They have been credited with robbing
the Mesquite Bank in Whites City...

509
00:49:50,864 --> 00:49:53,742
...and the J.J. Landry Oil Refinery
in Arp...

510
00:49:53,909 --> 00:49:55,160
- ...Texas...
- Arp.

511
00:49:55,327 --> 00:49:58,997
...the Sanger City National Bank
in Sanger, Indiana...

512
00:49:59,164 --> 00:50:02,542
...and the Lancaster Bank in Denton,
Texas, on three different occasions.

513
00:50:02,709 --> 00:50:05,504
In addition to these robberies,
the fast-traveling Barrows...

514
00:50:05,671 --> 00:50:07,589
...have been rumored
to have had a hand...

515
00:50:07,756 --> 00:50:10,175
...in the robbing of two
Piggly Wiggly stores...

516
00:50:11,051 --> 00:50:15,931
...in Texas
and one A&P store in Missouri.

517
00:50:16,098 --> 00:50:19,935
Though Chief Percy Hammond, who first
identified Clyde Barrow's brother, Buck...

518
00:50:20,102 --> 00:50:21,687
- Oh, Lord.
-...as a member..."

519
00:50:21,853 --> 00:50:24,231
We ain't gonna see another toilet
for 30 miles.

520
00:50:24,398 --> 00:50:26,858
Why don't you pull up over here?
Over here.

521
00:50:38,537 --> 00:50:40,247
Hey, now, here's something.

522
00:50:40,414 --> 00:50:43,291
"Lone cop arrests two officers
in hunt for Barrow.

523
00:50:43,458 --> 00:50:47,129
Police officer Howard Anderson's heart
turned faster than his motorcycle...

524
00:50:47,295 --> 00:50:50,632
...when he forced to the side of the road
a black V-eight sedan...

525
00:50:50,799 --> 00:50:54,594
...in which were three men and a
blonde-headed woman yesterday afternoon.

526
00:51:16,658 --> 00:51:20,245
He was certain he'd caught Clyde Barrow,
Bonnie Parker, maybe Buck Barrow...

527
00:51:20,412 --> 00:51:23,081
-...and the third unidentified member.
- Heh-heh. Well...

528
00:51:23,248 --> 00:51:25,959
It took a lot of telephoning
and explaining to convince...

529
00:51:26,126 --> 00:51:29,379
...the motorcycle cop that his captives
were two highway patrolmen...

530
00:51:29,546 --> 00:51:32,549
...and a blonde-haired stenographer
from the highway patrol.

531
00:51:35,177 --> 00:51:36,845
Anderson was held up as an example...

532
00:51:37,012 --> 00:51:39,097
...for every other
Texas police officer today..."

533
00:51:39,264 --> 00:51:40,640
Sheriff!

534
00:51:42,851 --> 00:51:45,187
30-hoo! 30-hoo!
I never seen such shooting!

535
00:51:45,353 --> 00:51:47,230
All right, all right.

536
00:51:47,397 --> 00:51:50,025
All right, now you just get
on right over to that car.

537
00:51:55,113 --> 00:51:58,950
Well, now, lookie here. We're in the
custody of Captain Frank Hammer.

538
00:51:59,117 --> 00:52:01,953
- And Frank here is a Texas Ranger.
- Sure enough is.

539
00:52:02,120 --> 00:52:03,121
Say, peacemaker...

540
00:52:03,288 --> 00:52:06,249
...I believe you got your spurs
all tangled up there, haven't you?

541
00:52:06,416 --> 00:52:09,085
- You're in Missouri. Know that?
- Know you're in Missouri?

542
00:52:09,252 --> 00:52:11,838
- He's lost, this Texas Ranger.
- I don't think he's lost.

543
00:52:12,005 --> 00:52:14,508
Them banks been offering
extra reward money for us...

544
00:52:14,674 --> 00:52:18,553
...and I think Frank just figured on
some easy pickings. Didn't you, Frank?

545
00:52:18,720 --> 00:52:21,097
You know, Texas Ranger,
you ain't doing your job.

546
00:52:21,264 --> 00:52:25,852
You ought to be home protecting the
rights of poor folk, not out chasing us.

547
00:52:26,019 --> 00:52:27,521
- Come on.
- Don't take it personal.

548
00:52:29,564 --> 00:52:32,526
- Protecting the poor folks.
- Why you wanna take it personal for?

549
00:52:32,692 --> 00:52:37,072
Well, we gotta discourage this here
bounty hunting for the Barrow Gang.

550
00:52:37,239 --> 00:52:40,158
Bounty? Huh?

551
00:52:40,325 --> 00:52:42,577
What do you wanna do
with him then, huh?

552
00:52:42,744 --> 00:52:44,454
- Shoot him?
- No!

553
00:52:46,414 --> 00:52:47,916
Come on, now. Huh?

554
00:52:48,917 --> 00:52:53,213
- Hang him. I don't know.
- Uh-uh. Take his picture.

555
00:52:53,505 --> 00:52:54,756
- Huh?
- Huh?

556
00:52:54,923 --> 00:52:57,425
- Take his picture?
- Listen, we take his picture...

557
00:52:57,592 --> 00:53:01,263
...we'll send it to the newspapers.
Frank just see Captain Frank Hammer...

558
00:53:01,429 --> 00:53:05,433
...of the Texas Rangers with the Barrow
Gang, and all of us just as friendly as pie.

559
00:53:06,810 --> 00:53:11,523
Now, you know, we are just about the
friendliest folks you'd ever wanna meet.

560
00:53:11,815 --> 00:53:16,194
Big old Texas Ranger
waves his gun at us...

561
00:53:16,361 --> 00:53:20,115
...and we just welcome him
like he was one of our own.

562
00:53:21,741 --> 00:53:23,493
- Hey, Buck, get the Kodak.
- Yeah.

563
00:53:23,660 --> 00:53:28,290
Hot doggies! Get him up there
on the spare tire, Clyde.

564
00:53:28,498 --> 00:53:31,084
Ha-ha-ha.
- All right. There we go, my friend.

565
00:53:31,251 --> 00:53:34,546
Now, see what come of your mischief
of not doing your job?

566
00:53:34,713 --> 00:53:37,048
You know, down in
Duncanville last year...

567
00:53:37,215 --> 00:53:41,177
...poor farmers kept you laws
away from us with shotguns. Hah.

568
00:53:41,803 --> 00:53:43,430
You're supposed to protect them from us.

569
00:53:43,597 --> 00:53:45,473
They protect us from you.
Don't make sense.

570
00:53:48,268 --> 00:53:50,896
You and Bonnie first.
Now, get right in there, now.

571
00:53:51,062 --> 00:53:53,023
Go on. Friendly, like, you know.

572
00:53:53,648 --> 00:53:57,152
When his Texas Ranger friends see
this, he's gonna wish he was dead.

573
00:53:57,319 --> 00:54:00,780
Well, we're mighty proud to have
a Texas Ranger in the family.

574
00:54:00,947 --> 00:54:01,990
Hold it, hold it.

575
00:54:03,575 --> 00:54:04,951
How's this?

576
00:54:05,118 --> 00:54:09,331
Oh, good, good, good. I'm getting it,
I'm getting it. Wait. Hold it. Duncanville!

577
00:54:12,417 --> 00:54:13,585
How about that?

578
00:54:15,003 --> 00:54:16,796
You has--

579
00:54:19,758 --> 00:54:21,051
Hold on, now.

580
00:54:25,263 --> 00:54:27,515
- Wet him down.
- I got the picture.

581
00:54:27,682 --> 00:54:30,352
I got-- I got--
I got the picture.

582
00:54:30,685 --> 00:54:33,063
- I got it! I got the--
- Ah!

583
00:54:33,688 --> 00:54:35,440
I got the picture! I got the--

584
00:54:36,775 --> 00:54:38,026
Oh, no.

585
00:54:39,778 --> 00:54:43,531
We're gonna put that picture
in every paper in the country!

586
00:54:43,698 --> 00:54:46,576
We got you! We got you.

587
00:54:46,743 --> 00:54:50,080
We got you now. We got you.

588
00:54:51,665 --> 00:54:55,710
Hey! We got you.
You just stay in there for a while.

589
00:54:55,877 --> 00:54:58,046
- I got the picture. Ha-ha-ha!
- We'll use that picture.

590
00:54:58,213 --> 00:55:01,299
We got you. We got--
We used you, boy.

591
00:55:01,466 --> 00:55:04,010
- We got you!
- Come on.

592
00:55:04,761 --> 00:55:06,304
Damn it.

593
00:55:20,235 --> 00:55:23,571
Ahem. Good afternoon.
This is the Barrow Gang.

594
00:55:25,073 --> 00:55:28,535
Now if everybody will just
take it easy, nobody will get hurt.

595
00:55:40,672 --> 00:55:43,258
- Is that your money or the bank's?
- Mine.

596
00:55:43,675 --> 00:55:45,510
All right, you keep it, then.

597
00:55:50,098 --> 00:55:52,100
Next time I'll aim a little lower.

598
00:55:57,272 --> 00:55:58,648
All right.

599
00:56:08,825 --> 00:56:10,452
Let's go.

600
00:56:14,414 --> 00:56:16,708
Take a good look, Pop.
I'm Buck Barrow.

601
00:56:19,961 --> 00:56:21,838
We're the Barrow boys!

602
00:56:22,505 --> 00:56:24,299
Come on!

603
00:56:28,303 --> 00:56:29,971
Happy birthday, hon.

604
00:56:43,860 --> 00:56:47,197
It was the Barrow Gang, Charlie.
I think they was headed for Oklahoma.

605
00:56:47,363 --> 00:56:52,118
Mommy, come!
Mommy, come! Now!

606
00:57:09,511 --> 00:57:11,137
Load this!

607
00:57:30,198 --> 00:57:34,536
There I was, staring square
into the face of death.

608
00:57:59,227 --> 00:58:03,398
And all I can say is
they did right by me...

609
00:58:03,565 --> 00:58:06,609
...and I'm bringing me a mess of flowers
to their funeral.

610
00:58:35,054 --> 00:58:37,098
Slow down, Clyde,
we're in Oklahoma now.

611
00:58:39,100 --> 00:58:40,560
Whew.

612
00:58:40,852 --> 00:58:42,770
Come on, let's catch them, anyway.

613
00:58:44,689 --> 00:58:47,400
I ain't gonna risk my life in Oklahoma.

614
00:59:10,298 --> 00:59:12,967
- Ain't much, is it?
- Well, times is hard.

615
00:59:15,136 --> 00:59:18,139
Well, let's get down to it.

616
00:59:20,099 --> 00:59:21,976
Mr. Buck.

617
00:59:23,811 --> 00:59:25,521
Bonnie Parker.

618
00:59:25,897 --> 00:59:27,982
C.W. Moss. Huh?

619
00:59:29,817 --> 00:59:30,818
Oh.

620
00:59:32,654 --> 00:59:34,864
I want my share.

621
00:59:36,115 --> 00:59:39,118
If Bonnie gets a share,
I want a share too.

622
00:59:39,285 --> 00:59:41,955
- What are you talking about?
- Tell Clyde I want my share.

623
00:59:42,121 --> 00:59:44,499
All right. All right.

624
00:59:46,668 --> 00:59:49,379
Clyde, uh,
what about Blanche here?

625
00:59:50,046 --> 00:59:51,506
What?

626
00:59:51,673 --> 00:59:53,424
Well, why not?

627
00:59:56,344 --> 00:59:59,430
Well, why not? I earned my share
same as everybody.

628
00:59:59,597 --> 01:00:03,685
I could have got killed same as everybody.
I'm wanted by the law same as everybody.

629
01:00:03,851 --> 01:00:07,522
Well, besides I could have got snake-bit
sleeping in them woods every night.

630
01:00:07,689 --> 01:00:10,358
I'm a nervous wreck
and that's the truth...

631
01:00:10,525 --> 01:00:14,529
...and I have to take sass
from Miss Bonnie Parker all the time.

632
01:00:14,696 --> 01:00:16,864
- I deserve mine!
- Hold on. Hold your horses.

633
01:00:17,031 --> 01:00:19,534
Blanche, you gonna get your share.

634
01:00:22,537 --> 01:00:24,080
Here.

635
01:00:26,874 --> 01:00:30,461
I married the preacher's daughter and she
thinks she's still taking up the collection.

636
01:00:33,631 --> 01:00:36,259
- Mrs. Buck Barrow.
- Thank you.

637
01:00:36,426 --> 01:00:39,721
Now, honey, don't spend it
all in one place.

638
01:00:43,850 --> 01:00:44,892
Hey.

639
01:00:45,852 --> 01:00:48,813
Listen now. Honey, I guess
I'm gonna have to keep saying this.

640
01:00:48,980 --> 01:00:51,607
Blanche is married to Buck,
and Buck is family.

641
01:00:51,774 --> 01:00:54,110
My family could use some of that money.

642
01:00:54,277 --> 01:00:58,323
Them laws been hanging around your
mama's house. It's too risky to go up now.

643
01:00:58,489 --> 01:01:01,743
But where can we go now? We rob
the damn banks. What else do we do?

644
01:01:01,909 --> 01:01:05,079
- Well, what you wanna do?
- Clyde. Clyde, there's a hole in the pan.

645
01:01:05,246 --> 01:01:09,584
We're losing oil. We gotta swipe another
car if we wanna get anywhere. Look.

646
01:01:14,213 --> 01:01:15,256
Huh?

647
01:01:16,090 --> 01:01:17,467
Stop that now.

648
01:01:19,260 --> 01:01:21,512
No, Eugene.

649
01:01:26,601 --> 01:01:28,269
Eugene.

650
01:01:30,396 --> 01:01:32,357
Come on!

651
01:01:32,523 --> 01:01:35,735
Stop that, Eugene.

652
01:01:35,902 --> 01:01:38,946
Say, isn't that your car, Eugene?

653
01:01:39,113 --> 01:01:40,490
That's my car.

654
01:01:43,868 --> 01:01:45,453
Hey.

655
01:01:46,204 --> 01:01:48,998
That's my car! Hey!

656
01:01:50,750 --> 01:01:52,960
That's my car!

657
01:02:08,976 --> 01:02:11,813
- Hey, they're coming after us.
- Come on, kick in the pants.

658
01:02:11,979 --> 01:02:15,733
I'm gonna tear them apart.
Those punks.

659
01:02:16,651 --> 01:02:18,486
Stealing a man's car.

660
01:02:19,821 --> 01:02:22,490
Wait till I get my hands
on those kids, Velma.

661
01:02:22,657 --> 01:02:25,284
I'm gonna tear them apart.

662
01:02:26,327 --> 01:02:29,455
What if they have guns, Eugene?

663
01:02:30,832 --> 01:02:34,127
Listen, we better get the police
and let them handle this.

664
01:02:34,293 --> 01:02:36,337
- Right.
- All right, now, turn around.

665
01:02:36,504 --> 01:02:40,007
Turn around and let's go back to town,
and we'll go get the sheriff.

666
01:02:44,345 --> 01:02:47,014
They stopped chasing us.
They're turning around there.

667
01:02:50,393 --> 01:02:52,937
- Let's take them.
- Good idea, Clyde.

668
01:02:58,359 --> 01:03:01,529
Oh, my Lord, they're coming after us.

669
01:03:02,071 --> 01:03:04,574
Step on it, Velma.
Velma, step on it, Velma.

670
01:03:04,740 --> 01:03:06,534
- Step on it, Velma.
- I am!

671
01:03:09,370 --> 01:03:11,247
What do you wanna do that for, Clyde?

672
01:03:11,414 --> 01:03:14,792
Step on it, Velma. Step on it, Velma.

673
01:03:16,210 --> 01:03:19,464
- Come on!
- Velma, step on it, Velma.

674
01:03:19,630 --> 01:03:21,048
Velma!

675
01:03:36,230 --> 01:03:39,275
- Howdy.
- Hey. Hey, what are you doing in there?

676
01:03:39,442 --> 01:03:41,736
Hey. Ain't it hot in there?

677
01:03:41,903 --> 01:03:45,615
- How are y'all?
- Hey, look what we got here.

678
01:03:54,165 --> 01:03:57,168
All right, get on out of there.
Come on, come on.

679
01:03:57,960 --> 01:04:01,464
You wanna go for a little ride
in our new car? Ah.

680
01:04:01,631 --> 01:04:03,925
- Oh, my, can we all fit in there?
- Come on.

681
01:04:04,091 --> 01:04:09,055
- I get to ride up front now. Finally.
- Come on. Come on. Come on.

682
01:04:10,765 --> 01:04:13,559
- There's not room for me in there.
- You all right?

683
01:04:25,947 --> 01:04:27,698
What's your names?

684
01:04:29,450 --> 01:04:33,287
I'm Eugene-- I'm Eugene Grizzard.

685
01:04:33,454 --> 01:04:35,623
And I'm Velma Davis.

686
01:04:35,790 --> 01:04:36,999
We're the Barrow Gang.

687
01:04:37,166 --> 01:04:42,213
That there's Clyde driving, I'm Buck,
that's my wife Blanche, Bonnie Parker, C.W.

688
01:04:42,463 --> 01:04:44,882
Oh, now listen, y'all, don't be scared.

689
01:04:45,049 --> 01:04:47,009
It ain't like you was the law or anything.

690
01:04:47,176 --> 01:04:50,805
- I mean, you're just folks, just like us.
- Yeah.

691
01:04:50,972 --> 01:04:52,056
Yeah, that's the truth.

692
01:04:54,308 --> 01:04:56,143
I expect you've been reading about us.

693
01:04:56,310 --> 01:04:57,812
- Oh, no.
- Yeah.

694
01:04:59,730 --> 01:05:01,357
Yes.

695
01:05:02,149 --> 01:05:04,151
We have too.

696
01:05:04,318 --> 01:05:08,823
Well, now, you two
must be in love, I bet, huh?

697
01:05:12,618 --> 01:05:14,662
Now, boy, when you
gonna marry the girl?

698
01:05:14,829 --> 01:05:16,330
- Buck.
- Ha-ha-ha.

699
01:05:24,171 --> 01:05:27,008
So he gave her the milk, see,
and she drank a little of it.

700
01:05:27,174 --> 01:05:32,179
The next day, he gave her some more and
she drank some more till one week goes by.

701
01:05:32,346 --> 01:05:35,516
And he brings her the milk and
she drinks down every drop of it.

702
01:05:35,683 --> 01:05:38,019
She looks at her son,
calls him over and says:

703
01:05:38,185 --> 01:05:41,063
"Son, whatever you do...

704
01:05:41,230 --> 01:05:42,565
...don't sell that cow."

705
01:05:45,776 --> 01:05:47,987
"Don't sell the cow."

706
01:05:58,039 --> 01:06:01,917
I'm from Wisconsin originally.
Where the cheese comes from.

707
01:06:03,377 --> 01:06:06,631
Oh, oh, but he just loves Texas now.
Don't you, Eugene?

708
01:06:06,797 --> 01:06:07,798
"Don't sell that cow."

709
01:06:09,925 --> 01:06:11,886
Hey, how old are you, honey?

710
01:06:12,470 --> 01:06:14,472
I'm 33.

711
01:06:30,488 --> 01:06:32,114
- There you go.
- Thanks, Buck.

712
01:06:32,281 --> 01:06:35,201
Now-- Now didn't I
order some French fries?

713
01:06:35,368 --> 01:06:37,870
Yeah, you did. Here you are.

714
01:06:38,829 --> 01:06:41,207
- Here you go.
- Thank you.

715
01:06:41,374 --> 01:06:45,127
Now take it easy on them French fries,
Velma. Ain't that right, Eugene?

716
01:06:45,294 --> 01:06:46,754
This isn't mine.

717
01:06:46,921 --> 01:06:50,174
I ordered mine well-done.
Who's got the other hamburger?

718
01:06:53,010 --> 01:06:55,262
Oh, is this supposed to be yours?

719
01:06:58,891 --> 01:07:01,102
It's okay. Forget it.

720
01:07:01,602 --> 01:07:02,770
I'm sure having a good time.

721
01:07:05,064 --> 01:07:06,649
Aren't you glad we picked you up?

722
01:07:06,816 --> 01:07:08,776
- You're a grand host, Buck.
- Yeah.

723
01:07:09,110 --> 01:07:10,945
Maybe y'all ought to join up with us.

724
01:07:15,032 --> 01:07:18,160
Boy, they sure would be surprised
to hear that back home.

725
01:07:18,327 --> 01:07:21,914
What would--? What would Bill
and Martha say if they heard that?

726
01:07:22,081 --> 01:07:24,500
Lordy, they would have a fit.

727
01:07:25,835 --> 01:07:27,628
Hey, what do you do, anyhow?

728
01:07:29,213 --> 01:07:31,132
I'm an undertaker.

729
01:07:35,678 --> 01:07:37,304
Get them out of here.

730
01:07:57,116 --> 01:07:59,910
Bonnie!

731
01:08:00,327 --> 01:08:02,037
Bonnie!

732
01:08:02,204 --> 01:08:05,958
- Bonnie!
- Bonnie.

733
01:08:06,959 --> 01:08:09,670
I don't see her, Clyde.

734
01:08:09,837 --> 01:08:11,881
Bonnie, where are you?

735
01:08:12,882 --> 01:08:15,259
Bonnie!

736
01:08:17,678 --> 01:08:21,182
Ahh. Bonnie!

737
01:08:24,185 --> 01:08:29,023
- Where do you think she could have went?
- Boy, I don't know. I just don't know.

738
01:08:34,695 --> 01:08:37,531
There! Bonnie!

739
01:08:38,824 --> 01:08:40,201
Bonnie!

740
01:08:44,246 --> 01:08:45,706
Bonnie.

741
01:08:51,420 --> 01:08:53,422
- Bonnie.
- Leave me alone!

742
01:08:53,589 --> 01:08:56,801
- Where are you going?
- Get away!

743
01:08:56,967 --> 01:08:58,844
- Bonnie. Honey.
- Oh-- Oh!

744
01:09:01,555 --> 01:09:04,934
I want-- I wanna see my mama.

745
01:09:05,226 --> 01:09:06,894
I wanna see my mama.

746
01:09:07,061 --> 01:09:11,690
Please, honey, don't ever leave me
without saying nothing.

747
01:09:14,068 --> 01:09:15,736
All right.

748
01:09:18,030 --> 01:09:23,285
But-- No, but Clyde, listen to me.
Clyde, please.

749
01:09:23,452 --> 01:09:27,456
Now listen to me, I mean it.
I been thinking about my mama...

750
01:09:27,623 --> 01:09:32,753
...and she's getting so old
and I wanna see her. Please, Clyde.

751
01:09:33,295 --> 01:09:34,505
- Please.
- We'll see her.

752
01:09:38,843 --> 01:09:40,344
We'll see her.

753
01:10:08,956 --> 01:10:11,292
Well, would you look at him?

754
01:10:13,127 --> 01:10:15,421
He just don't remember me.

755
01:10:16,755 --> 01:10:18,883
He'll get used to me, won't he?

756
01:10:19,633 --> 01:10:22,720
We've been cutting and pasting
everything we could find about you.

757
01:10:22,887 --> 01:10:25,306
Hey, hey, Clyde,
there's the shot I took of you.

758
01:10:25,472 --> 01:10:27,474
It turned out real fine, didn't it, huh?

759
01:11:07,181 --> 01:11:10,935
Oh, Lord, we thank thee
for the safety of our loved ones...

760
01:11:11,101 --> 01:11:13,187
...and the food we are
about to receive. Amen.

761
01:11:27,868 --> 01:11:29,203
- Bye, Clyde.
- Bye-bye.

762
01:11:29,370 --> 01:11:32,373
Y'all be careful.
We're gonna miss you, now.

763
01:11:35,084 --> 01:11:37,211
Where you all headed to
from here, Clyde?

764
01:11:37,378 --> 01:11:40,214
At this point we ain't heading to
nowhere. We just running from.

765
01:11:41,548 --> 01:11:43,050
Clyde.

766
01:11:43,550 --> 01:11:45,928
Tom, we're going home.

767
01:11:46,845 --> 01:11:51,642
Little Tom.
Matthew, fetch little Tom.

768
01:11:52,476 --> 01:11:54,061
Mama. Listen.

769
01:11:54,228 --> 01:11:59,400
Mama, why don't you stay
a little while longer, huh? Okay?

770
01:11:59,566 --> 01:12:01,735
Listen, I want you to have this.

771
01:12:01,902 --> 01:12:06,699
- Come on, boys.
- Come on, we gotta go home.

772
01:12:09,284 --> 01:12:13,455
Clyde? Sugar, listen, make Mama
stay a while yet, huh?

773
01:12:13,622 --> 01:12:17,960
You know, Clyde,
I read about you all in the papers...

774
01:12:18,127 --> 01:12:21,463
...and I just get scared.

775
01:12:21,797 --> 01:12:25,426
Now, Mrs. Parker, don't you believe
what you read in all them newspapers.

776
01:12:25,592 --> 01:12:27,136
That's the laws talking there.

777
01:12:27,302 --> 01:12:30,431
They want us to look big so
they can look big when they catch us.

778
01:12:30,597 --> 01:12:34,184
They won't catch us. I'm even better
at running than I am at robbing banks. Heh.

779
01:12:34,935 --> 01:12:37,396
Shoot, if we done half that stuff
they say we done...

780
01:12:37,563 --> 01:12:39,106
...we'd be millionaires by now.

781
01:12:39,273 --> 01:12:40,607
Yeah.

782
01:12:40,774 --> 01:12:43,318
I ain't gonna risk my little girl
just to make money...

783
01:12:43,485 --> 01:12:44,945
...uncertain as times are.

784
01:12:45,946 --> 01:12:47,531
Why, I BUCK LAUGHS of a job...

785
01:12:48,282 --> 01:12:51,410
You remember the time?
Why, we could have gotten $2000..

786
01:12:51,577 --> 01:12:53,120
...just as easy as pie.

787
01:12:53,287 --> 01:12:57,332
And I pulled up outside there
and I saw them laws...

788
01:12:57,499 --> 01:13:01,003
...and I said to myself, I said,
"Bonnie could get hurt here."

789
01:13:01,170 --> 01:13:03,505
So we just drove right on
and I let that money lay.

790
01:13:03,672 --> 01:13:06,216
Maybe you know the way with her, then.

791
01:13:06,383 --> 01:13:07,551
I'm just an old woman.

792
01:13:07,718 --> 01:13:09,511
- I don't know nothing.
- Mrs. Parker.

793
01:13:09,678 --> 01:13:13,182
But Mrs. Parker, this here is the
way we know best how to make money.

794
01:13:13,348 --> 01:13:16,769
We gonna quit this as soon as
hard times are over, I can tell you that.

795
01:13:16,935 --> 01:13:19,980
Why, just the other night,
me and Bonnie were talking...

796
01:13:20,147 --> 01:13:23,942
We were talking about the time we were
gonna settle down and get us a home.

797
01:13:25,194 --> 01:13:29,656
She says to me, she says,
"You know, I couldn't bear...

798
01:13:29,823 --> 01:13:32,993
...to live more than three miles
from my precious mother."

799
01:13:33,994 --> 01:13:36,163
Now, how'd you like that,
Mother Parker?

800
01:13:36,330 --> 01:13:38,332
I don't believe I would.

801
01:13:38,874 --> 01:13:40,667
I surely don't.

802
01:13:41,794 --> 01:13:46,048
You try to live three miles from me
and you won't live long, honey.

803
01:13:47,091 --> 01:13:49,843
You best keep running, Clyde Barrow.

804
01:13:50,427 --> 01:13:51,512
And you know it.

805
01:13:56,350 --> 01:13:58,435
Bye,baby.

806
01:14:12,866 --> 01:14:16,036
- Goodbye, y'all.
- Bye.

807
01:14:23,085 --> 01:14:25,212
Look, who is this there?
Is that your girlfriend? Hmm?

808
01:14:27,714 --> 01:14:29,424
L-O-V-E.

809
01:14:29,967 --> 01:14:31,885
Well, whose idea was it
to get bluebirds?

810
01:14:32,052 --> 01:14:35,806
- Bonnie's. Bonnie picked it out.
- Bonnie?

811
01:14:35,973 --> 01:14:38,600
Day after we robbed the armory.

812
01:14:38,934 --> 01:14:42,229
Hey, hon, come over here.
I want you to touch something here.

813
01:14:42,396 --> 01:14:45,315
- No.
- I want you just to touch it right there.

814
01:14:45,482 --> 01:14:46,817
Go on, now.

815
01:14:51,071 --> 01:14:52,614
Sweet and sour!

816
01:14:52,781 --> 01:14:55,868
Why don't you all
go into your own cabin...

817
01:14:56,034 --> 01:14:57,911
...if you wanna play with C.W.?

818
01:14:58,078 --> 01:15:01,290
What's the matter with you,
besides your nasty disposition?

819
01:15:01,456 --> 01:15:04,084
- Let me handle it.
- No. Why does she have to wait'?

820
01:15:04,251 --> 01:15:06,128
Hold on. Hold on!

821
01:15:07,796 --> 01:15:11,592
I saw a chicken place a few miles back.
Who all wants to get some food?

822
01:15:11,758 --> 01:15:14,178
I certainly do. I'm sick to death
of sitting around.

823
01:15:14,344 --> 01:15:17,222
- You can't even drive the car.
<i>- I'll</i> go. What do y'all want?

824
01:15:17,389 --> 01:15:20,684
Just get us five chicken dinners.

825
01:15:22,644 --> 01:15:27,316
Hey, get some dessert there too, some
peach ice cream or something, will you?

826
01:15:51,465 --> 01:15:55,427
Oh, baby, I got the blues so bad.

827
01:15:59,723 --> 01:16:01,141
Yeah.

828
01:16:06,271 --> 01:16:08,607
Well, is it what your mama said?

829
01:16:12,861 --> 01:16:14,821
What mama?

830
01:16:17,366 --> 01:16:20,160
She's just an old woman now.

831
01:16:21,495 --> 01:16:23,830
I don't have no mama.

832
01:16:26,792 --> 01:16:29,169
No family either.

833
01:16:30,629 --> 01:16:33,882
Hey, I'm your family.

834
01:16:49,231 --> 01:16:51,775
You know, when we started out...

835
01:16:51,942 --> 01:16:55,696
...I thought we was
really going somewhere.

836
01:16:57,656 --> 01:16:59,783
But this is it.

837
01:17:02,202 --> 01:17:03,954
We're just going, huh?

838
01:17:07,124 --> 01:17:08,959
I love you.

839
01:17:22,931 --> 01:17:25,559
- You sure are smoking a lot lately.
- So what?

840
01:17:26,935 --> 01:17:28,562
Nothing.

841
01:17:30,814 --> 01:17:32,899
Oh, Lord.

842
01:17:34,234 --> 01:17:36,903
Why don't you go back
to your pa's house?

843
01:17:38,905 --> 01:17:40,741
If I only could.

844
01:17:41,366 --> 01:17:44,494
If I could only just do that one thing.

845
01:17:46,580 --> 01:17:49,666
There's no telling
how all this happened.

846
01:17:50,292 --> 01:17:52,919
I was a preacher's daughter.

847
01:17:54,379 --> 01:17:58,467
- What church was your pa affiliated with?
- Baptist.

848
01:18:06,058 --> 01:18:08,935
He thought the world of Buck,
my daddy did.

849
01:18:09,353 --> 01:18:12,647
Even though Buck
was serving time in jail.

850
01:18:14,733 --> 01:18:18,445
He forgave him
because he paid his debt to society.

851
01:18:20,405 --> 01:18:22,032
We were Disciples of Christ.

852
01:18:33,543 --> 01:18:36,588
Hey, I ain't got no money.
Give me some, will you?

853
01:18:56,817 --> 01:19:00,153
Get me Sheriff Smoot on the phone.
Yeah.

854
01:19:15,919 --> 01:19:17,879
That's more like it.

855
01:19:18,046 --> 01:19:20,674
Look how much better
it fits since I took it up.

856
01:19:29,516 --> 01:19:31,601
The men are on the other side.

857
01:19:33,854 --> 01:19:35,439
All right, let go.

858
01:20:10,974 --> 01:20:14,269
C.W., C.W., grenades.

859
01:20:47,761 --> 01:20:49,262
Hold it, hold it!

860
01:20:49,763 --> 01:20:51,264
Get out!

861
01:20:54,976 --> 01:20:56,478
Wait, Buck!

862
01:20:59,689 --> 01:21:00,815
Get out!

863
01:21:13,620 --> 01:21:15,830
Bring your fire around there.

864
01:21:19,459 --> 01:21:20,794
- No!
- Oh!

865
01:21:56,413 --> 01:21:58,039
Get on!

866
01:22:02,377 --> 01:22:04,588
Give me a gun, please!
I don't have a gun.

867
01:22:05,922 --> 01:22:08,508
- Listen to me.
- Get down. Stop that. You going crazy?

868
01:22:08,675 --> 01:22:09,843
Oh, no!

869
01:22:10,010 --> 01:22:13,054
Please be quiet! Please be quiet!
We're trying to get out.

870
01:22:38,955 --> 01:22:42,375
It didn't happen, Daddy.
It didn't happen. I know it--

871
01:22:44,127 --> 01:22:46,963
- Blanche, stop that!
- You stop it!

872
01:23:05,398 --> 01:23:08,443
I'd rather go to jail
than go on like this.

873
01:23:10,779 --> 01:23:13,782
He ain't got a chance.
Half his head's blown off.

874
01:23:13,948 --> 01:23:16,826
- Here we go.
- Oh, God. Oh, God.

875
01:23:16,993 --> 01:23:21,665
Dear Lord, it happened.
Please help us.

876
01:23:21,831 --> 01:23:25,877
And Buck will never do anything
wrong again in his life.

877
01:23:28,505 --> 01:23:30,131
My eyes!

878
01:23:31,633 --> 01:23:33,426
I think I'm blind.

879
01:23:33,927 --> 01:23:36,096
MY eyes!

880
01:23:36,262 --> 01:23:38,181
The light hurts so bad!

881
01:23:38,682 --> 01:23:41,726
- The light hurts so bad!
- Here, hon, here.

882
01:23:44,729 --> 01:23:46,022
There.

883
01:23:46,189 --> 01:23:48,483
- Tell Clyde to get us to a doctor.
- Shh.

884
01:23:48,650 --> 01:23:50,819
Bonnie! We are dying!

885
01:23:50,985 --> 01:23:53,530
Buck can't be moved now, hon. Shh.

886
01:23:54,114 --> 01:24:00,078
- Clyde! Clyde! Clyde.
- I'm right here, boy.

887
01:24:01,121 --> 01:24:03,915
I believe I lost my shoes, Clyde.

888
01:24:04,958 --> 01:24:07,127
I think the dog got them.

889
01:24:41,661 --> 01:24:42,746
Surrender!

890
01:24:43,705 --> 01:24:45,165
- Buck, in the car.
- Surrender!

891
01:24:48,168 --> 01:24:49,294
Come on, keep low!

892
01:25:09,939 --> 01:25:12,192
Hey, Clyde, we're going this way.

893
01:25:15,695 --> 01:25:18,782
Crossfire! Keep low! Crossfire.

894
01:25:34,547 --> 01:25:35,924
Move up!

895
01:25:36,591 --> 01:25:39,552
Charlie, don't shoot!
The kids are in the crossfire!

896
01:25:39,719 --> 01:25:42,555
- I'll go get the car. I'll get the car.
- Buck.

897
01:25:42,722 --> 01:25:44,891
Now, Buck, this way.

898
01:25:45,225 --> 01:25:46,810
- Come out through here.
- Buck!

899
01:25:46,976 --> 01:25:50,730
They're heading for the other car!
Shoot it! Knock the hell out of it!

900
01:26:13,419 --> 01:26:14,921
Hold your fire!

901
01:26:15,088 --> 01:26:17,674
Daddy, don't die!

902
01:26:20,218 --> 01:26:22,303
- Hold your fire!
- Leave him alone.

903
01:26:22,470 --> 01:26:26,349
He's dying. Can't you see he's dying?
You gotta let me go! Daddy!

904
01:26:26,516 --> 01:26:31,604
You killed him! He's dying!
God, can't you see him dying?

905
01:26:33,523 --> 01:26:36,818
Daddy. Don't. Daddy!

906
01:26:36,985 --> 01:26:41,823
Don't! Oh, Daddy.

907
01:26:41,990 --> 01:26:43,533
Daddy!

908
01:27:28,703 --> 01:27:30,288
- Maybe--
- Shh!

909
01:27:31,331 --> 01:27:32,790
Shh.

910
01:29:15,018 --> 01:29:18,855
Can you all
spare us some drinking water?

911
01:29:19,022 --> 01:29:21,774
- Who are you, boy?
- My name is Moss.

912
01:30:00,146 --> 01:30:02,315
That's Clyde Barrow and Bonnie Parker.

913
01:30:02,482 --> 01:30:04,233
What happened to them?

914
01:30:04,400 --> 01:30:05,985
Hush.

915
01:30:08,071 --> 01:30:09,489
Are they famous?

916
01:30:29,592 --> 01:30:33,137
- Is that really Bonnie Parker?
- Yeah.

917
01:31:02,542 --> 01:31:06,087
Daddy! Daddy!

918
01:31:08,131 --> 01:31:09,507
- Who's there? Huh?
- C.W.

919
01:31:09,674 --> 01:31:11,467
- Clarence.
- Clarence.

920
01:31:11,634 --> 01:31:14,512
Oh, it's good to see you, boy.
Oh, boy, it's good to see you.

921
01:31:14,679 --> 01:31:17,557
- What's that on your chest?
- A tattoo, Daddy. Come on.

922
01:31:18,182 --> 01:31:19,684
Come on.

923
01:31:20,184 --> 01:31:21,936
- You gotta help them.
- Huh?

924
01:31:23,729 --> 01:31:25,565
Help me get them in.

925
01:31:26,607 --> 01:31:29,277
What happened to them?
Are you in trouble, son?

926
01:31:29,735 --> 01:31:31,821
Clyde Barrow and Bonnie Parker.

927
01:31:32,113 --> 01:31:34,991
Come on. Help me get them in.

928
01:31:45,543 --> 01:31:48,796
How come you marked yourself
all up with that tattoo?

929
01:31:49,130 --> 01:31:52,175
What the hell made you do
a damn fool thing like that?

930
01:31:53,593 --> 01:31:57,263
- You hear me?
- Just open the door, Daddy.

931
01:32:07,190 --> 01:32:09,317
I come here to question Blanche Barrow.

932
01:32:09,483 --> 01:32:13,279
- So you're the Frank Hammer, huh?
- Hammer.

933
01:32:14,947 --> 01:32:17,825
I figure to have my picture
took with them two...

934
01:32:17,992 --> 01:32:20,119
...just one more time.

935
01:32:21,454 --> 01:32:23,956
It says here Clyde fled
his dying brother.

936
01:32:24,123 --> 01:32:25,458
What do they mean, fled?

937
01:32:25,625 --> 01:32:29,795
How could I leave my brother to die
when he was already dead when I left him?

938
01:32:29,962 --> 01:32:31,464
Fled!

939
01:32:32,131 --> 01:32:34,592
Newspapers.

940
01:32:34,759 --> 01:32:36,177
While we're around here near dead...

941
01:32:36,344 --> 01:32:39,388
...they said we held up
the Grand Prairie National Bank.

942
01:32:39,555 --> 01:32:41,724
Guess they hung that
one on us just for luck.

943
01:32:41,891 --> 01:32:47,772
I'll tell you, as soon as we get well, we
gonna hold up that bank! We gonna take it!

944
01:33:00,159 --> 01:33:02,453
They don't know nothing, do they, honey?

945
01:33:02,620 --> 01:33:06,082
Hey, how come they're always
referring to me, the newspapers, as...

946
01:33:06,249 --> 01:33:11,087
-...unidentified suspect?
- You just be glad that's all you are.

947
01:33:11,254 --> 01:33:13,089
Long as they don't know your last name.

948
01:33:13,256 --> 01:33:18,010
That's right, boy. Mr. Barrow's
looking out for your interests.

949
01:33:20,096 --> 01:33:21,764
Hey,Pa.Heh.

950
01:33:21,931 --> 01:33:25,184
How does it feel to have a couple
of big deals stay in your house?

951
01:33:25,351 --> 01:33:27,353
That's something for me, ain't it?

952
01:33:27,520 --> 01:33:29,355
You've been mighty nice to us.

953
01:33:29,730 --> 01:33:34,610
And I want you to let us pay you,
say, $40 for your hospitality.

954
01:33:34,777 --> 01:33:40,533
No, no. no. I'm just happy to
have y'all folks here as company.

955
01:33:40,700 --> 01:33:42,785
Anybody's a friend of
my boy, you know, l...

956
01:33:43,077 --> 01:33:45,705
Come on, let's go have some supper.
I'm starving.

957
01:33:47,039 --> 01:33:50,126
Y'all are welcome here.
You know that.

958
01:33:50,793 --> 01:33:55,339
And you just make yourself right at
home and stay as long as you want to.

959
01:34:03,264 --> 01:34:06,267
You look like trash,
all marked up like that.

960
01:34:07,935 --> 01:34:09,603
Cheap trash!

961
01:34:11,731 --> 01:34:13,733
Bonnie says it looks good.

962
01:34:14,859 --> 01:34:17,862
What does Bonnie know? She ain't
nothing but cheap trash herself.

963
01:34:18,029 --> 01:34:20,865
Look what they do.
Don't ever get your name in the paper.

964
01:34:21,032 --> 01:34:24,160
You just get them pictures printed
on your skin by Bonnie and Clyde.

965
01:34:24,327 --> 01:34:27,496
Shoot, they ain't nothing
but a couple of kids.

966
01:34:28,205 --> 01:34:30,833
- But, Daddy...
- I'm so glad your ma ain't alive...

967
01:34:31,000 --> 01:34:33,085
...to see this here thing. Hah!

968
01:34:34,879 --> 01:34:37,256
- All jellied up like that!
- Ah!

969
01:34:38,507 --> 01:34:42,261
I don't see what's so bad about it.

970
01:34:43,429 --> 01:34:45,181
You wouldn't.

971
01:34:48,184 --> 01:34:49,393
All right, I'll go.

972
01:34:49,560 --> 01:34:54,106
Look, the word is out that Bonnie and
Clyde are holed up just out of town.

973
01:34:54,273 --> 01:34:57,860
And they're fixing to bust in here
and take Blanche out. So...

974
01:34:58,736 --> 01:35:00,863
All two of them?

975
01:35:21,592 --> 01:35:23,094
- Blanche Barrow.
- Ahh!

976
01:35:24,303 --> 01:35:26,055
Who is it?

977
01:35:35,356 --> 01:35:40,486
I guess it's been kind of
rough on you, hasn't it?

978
01:35:43,030 --> 01:35:45,825
Being the daughter of a preacher,
like you are.

979
01:35:57,670 --> 01:36:01,507
I imagine old Buck wasn't
a bad sort, was he?

980
01:36:02,007 --> 01:36:04,176
No, he wasn't.

981
01:36:05,052 --> 01:36:06,804
I reckon...

982
01:36:07,680 --> 01:36:10,099
...Clyde just sort of...

983
01:36:10,808 --> 01:36:13,561
...led him astray, didn't he?

984
01:36:22,736 --> 01:36:25,448
That's a shame, Blanche.

985
01:36:29,243 --> 01:36:33,372
Yes, ma'am. That's a shame.

986
01:36:34,498 --> 01:36:37,710
They done led your Buck astray.

987
01:36:37,960 --> 01:36:40,838
Clyde, his own brother...

988
01:36:41,005 --> 01:36:42,631
...Bonnie.

989
01:36:43,549 --> 01:36:45,676
And that little feller.

990
01:36:46,635 --> 01:36:50,222
The one that was with you when you
took that Texas Ranger in Missouri.

991
01:36:53,851 --> 01:36:56,812
He was with you all along, wasn't he?

992
01:37:01,400 --> 01:37:03,402
C.W.

993
01:37:04,069 --> 01:37:07,239
That's right, C.W.

994
01:37:10,034 --> 01:37:11,035
I, uh...

995
01:37:12,161 --> 01:37:14,955
I don't recollect his last name.

996
01:37:16,749 --> 01:37:17,791
Moss.

997
01:37:18,584 --> 01:37:20,794
C.W. Moss.

998
01:37:21,086 --> 01:37:23,088
He was there that day we met them.

999
01:37:23,255 --> 01:37:27,343
I didn't wanna go. I didn't want to.

1000
01:37:27,510 --> 01:37:31,514
And Buck said we was just
going on a visit...

1001
01:37:31,680 --> 01:37:35,017
...and we wouldn't
do no stealing or robbing.

1002
01:37:36,560 --> 01:37:40,147
And we went up to Joplin,
and all of a sudden...

1003
01:37:40,314 --> 01:37:41,398
All of a sudden...

1004
01:37:41,565 --> 01:37:43,526
...they all just started shooting.

1005
01:37:54,537 --> 01:37:55,955
What you writing?

1006
01:37:56,121 --> 01:37:59,208
I'm writing a poem about us.

1007
01:37:59,375 --> 01:38:01,794
- Yeah? Let me hear it.
- Mm-hm.

1008
01:38:03,170 --> 01:38:06,799
- Come on.
- Okay. Just let me finish this line.

1009
01:38:08,884 --> 01:38:13,013
Um... It's called
"The Story of Bonnie and Clyde."

1010
01:38:13,180 --> 01:38:17,935
<i>You've heard the story of Jesse James
Of how he lived and died.</i>

1011
01:38:18,102 --> 01:38:20,938
<i>If you're still in need
Of something to read</i>

1012
01:38:21,105 --> 01:38:24,149
<i>Here's the story of Bonnie and Clyde.</i>

1013
01:38:24,316 --> 01:38:27,778
You think if I sent that into
the newspapers, they'd print it?

1014
01:38:29,363 --> 01:38:31,031
I'm gonna do it.

1015
01:38:31,699 --> 01:38:36,161
<i>Now Bonnie and Clyde are the Barrow Gang
I'm sure you all have read.</i>

1016
01:38:36,328 --> 01:38:39,290
<i>How they rob and steal
And those who squeal</i>

1017
01:38:39,456 --> 01:38:42,209
<i>Are usually found dying or dead.</i>

1018
01:38:42,376 --> 01:38:46,046
<i>They call them cold-Smoot killers</i>

1019
01:38:46,213 --> 01:38:48,841
<i>They say they are heartless and mean</i>

1020
01:38:49,008 --> 01:38:52,845
<i>But I say this with pride
That I once knew Clyde</i>

1021
01:38:53,012 --> 01:38:55,889
<i>When he was honest
And upright and clean.</i>

1022
01:38:56,307 --> 01:38:59,518
<i>But the laws fooled around
Kept taking him down</i>

1023
01:38:59,685 --> 01:39:01,687
<i>And locking him up in a cell.</i>

1024
01:39:01,854 --> 01:39:06,942
<i>Till he said to me, "I'll never be free
So I'll meet a few of them in hell."</i>

1025
01:39:07,109 --> 01:39:12,197
<i>if a policeman is killed in Dallas
And they have no clue to guide.</i>

1026
01:39:12,364 --> 01:39:15,701
<i>If they can't find a fiend,
They just wipe their slate clean</i>

1027
01:39:15,868 --> 01:39:18,621
<i>And hang it on Bonnie and Clyde</i>

1028
01:39:18,787 --> 01:39:21,415
<i>If they try to act like citizens</i>

1029
01:39:21,582 --> 01:39:24,209
<i>And rent them a nice little flat</i>

1030
01:39:24,376 --> 01:39:27,171
<i>About the third night
They're invited to fight</i>

1031
01:39:27,338 --> 01:39:30,382
<i>By a sub-gun's rat-a-tat-tat.</i>

1032
01:39:30,549 --> 01:39:32,718
<i>Someday they'll go down together</i>

1033
01:39:32,885 --> 01:39:35,012
<i>They'll bury them side by side.</i>

1034
01:39:35,179 --> 01:39:38,307
<i>To few it'll be grief
To the law a relief</i>

1035
01:39:38,474 --> 01:39:41,060
<i>But it's death for Bonnie and Clyde.</i>

1036
01:39:46,398 --> 01:39:50,319
You know what you done there?
You told my story.

1037
01:39:50,819 --> 01:39:53,906
You told my whole story right there.
Right there.

1038
01:39:55,407 --> 01:39:59,286
One time I told you I was gonna make you
somebody. That's what you done for me.

1039
01:39:59,870 --> 01:40:02,915
You made me somebody
they gonna remember.

1040
01:41:37,301 --> 01:41:39,011
Damn.

1041
01:41:40,179 --> 01:41:42,181
- Hey, how you feel?
- Fine.

1042
01:41:42,347 --> 01:41:45,142
You feel the way you're supposed to feel
when you--? After--?

1043
01:41:45,309 --> 01:41:47,853
- Yeah, just.
- Mm-hm.

1044
01:41:48,145 --> 01:41:51,482
Well, that's-- That's good, isn't it?

1045
01:41:52,191 --> 01:41:55,903
Look, I-- I figure
it's a good idea to ask...

1046
01:41:56,069 --> 01:41:58,363
...because how else are
you gonna know if it...?

1047
01:41:58,530 --> 01:42:02,826
Hey. You did just perfect.

1048
01:42:05,579 --> 01:42:06,705
I did, didn't I?

1049
01:42:10,042 --> 01:42:12,085
I mean, I really did.

1050
01:42:13,045 --> 01:42:15,047
I never figured on that. Damn.

1051
01:42:18,217 --> 01:42:22,221
Clyde, now why do you wanna marry me?

1052
01:42:24,681 --> 01:42:27,309
To make an honest woman out of you.

1053
01:42:31,647 --> 01:42:33,774
What would you do...?

1054
01:42:33,941 --> 01:42:39,363
What would you do
if some miracle happened...

1055
01:42:40,572 --> 01:42:43,826
...and we could walk out of here
tomorrow morning...

1056
01:42:43,992 --> 01:42:47,371
...and start all over again clean...

1057
01:42:47,538 --> 01:42:51,959
...with no record and nobody after us?

1058
01:42:52,668 --> 01:42:53,669
Hmm?

1059
01:43:00,676 --> 01:43:02,010
Well...

1060
01:43:03,971 --> 01:43:06,431
I guess I'd do it all different.

1061
01:43:09,601 --> 01:43:11,436
First off...

1062
01:43:12,354 --> 01:43:15,232
...I wouldn't live in the same state
where we pull our jobs.

1063
01:43:15,399 --> 01:43:18,151
I mean, we'd live in another state
and stay clean there.

1064
01:43:18,318 --> 01:43:21,738
And then when we wanted to take
a bank, we'd go into the other state.

1065
01:43:25,242 --> 01:43:26,493
Huh?

1066
01:43:29,162 --> 01:43:30,664
Bonnie?

1067
01:43:37,629 --> 01:43:39,298
Bonnie.

1068
01:43:46,680 --> 01:43:49,391
Boy, did they expect you to go
downtown with them tomorrow?

1069
01:43:49,558 --> 01:43:50,809
Who?

1070
01:43:50,976 --> 01:43:52,644
Bonnie and Clyde, that's who.

1071
01:43:52,811 --> 01:43:54,980
Sure, I always go with them.

1072
01:43:58,150 --> 01:43:59,192
Yeah.

1073
01:44:00,277 --> 01:44:03,947
Yeah, you'd better. You'd better go.

1074
01:44:05,157 --> 01:44:07,910
But when they go to get in their car
to come on home...

1075
01:44:08,076 --> 01:44:10,704
-...don't get back in there with them.
- Why, Daddy?

1076
01:44:10,871 --> 01:44:13,081
You listen to your pa for once,
can you do that?

1077
01:44:13,248 --> 01:44:16,960
I'm your pa, I'm your kin!
Not that there Clyde Barrow.

1078
01:44:17,419 --> 01:44:20,839
What do you want me to tell them,
"I can't get back in the car with you"?

1079
01:44:21,006 --> 01:44:23,050
You tell them nothing, you hear?

1080
01:44:25,677 --> 01:44:29,514
I made a deal and got you off
with a couple of years.

1081
01:44:29,890 --> 01:44:32,851
You just be sure that you're
off the streets in that town...

1082
01:44:33,018 --> 01:44:34,895
...when they go to get in their car.

1083
01:44:35,062 --> 01:44:38,231
You think laws are gonna
catch Bonnie and Clyde in town?

1084
01:44:38,398 --> 01:44:41,985
Clyde's got a sense.
Don't you know that, Daddy?

1085
01:44:42,361 --> 01:44:45,614
Nobody catches Clyde. Never.

1086
01:44:49,034 --> 01:44:50,744
Never!

1087
01:45:21,108 --> 01:45:22,526
What happened to C.W.?

1088
01:45:22,693 --> 01:45:27,030
He's over there in the hardware store
getting some light bulbs for his daddy.

1089
01:45:33,745 --> 01:45:38,000
- Huh. You gonna wear them like that?
- Drive with one eye closed.

1090
01:45:40,252 --> 01:45:42,004
- Want some ice cream?
- No.

1091
01:45:42,170 --> 01:45:45,173
Look here. Isn't that just
the prettiest thing you ever saw?

1092
01:45:45,340 --> 01:45:48,552
Look, you see, you can see
every fingernail of her hand. Look.

1093
01:45:48,719 --> 01:45:51,179
That's the prettiest thing.
Hey, where is that boy?

1094
01:45:51,346 --> 01:45:53,724
Listen, I'll go get him, okay?

1095
01:46:26,715 --> 01:46:29,468
Gladys Jean!
Time to go home now.

1096
01:47:06,463 --> 01:47:09,841
We'll get back there in about 20 minutes
and we'll pick him up.

1097
01:47:11,843 --> 01:47:15,013
I tell you, if that boy didn't have
his head strapped on him, he'd lose it.

1098
01:47:42,249 --> 01:47:45,502
Hey, isn't that Malcolm there?

1099
01:48:04,563 --> 01:48:05,605
What you got there?

1100
01:48:05,772 --> 01:48:07,983
I got a flat tire. I ain't got no spare.

1101
01:48:23,582 --> 01:48:24,666
Hey.

